</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,623,828]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Described originally from 
<collectingCountry box="[462,554,624,647]" name="Panama" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Panama</collectingCountry>
, with a synonym described from 
<collectingCountry box="[954,1042,623,647]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, this species is closely similar in structure, sculpture and chaetotaxy to 
<taxonomicName box="[589,672,661,684]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Frankliniella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varipes">
<emphasis box="[589,672,661,684]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">varipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with long pronotal setae, little pronotal sculpture, and fore wings that are bicoloured. The only difference found on the available specimens is that the mid tibiae of 
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1393,696,720]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Frankliniella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulipes">
<emphasis box="[1284,1393,696,720]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">annulipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are brown but sharply yellow on the basal third, whereas those of 
<taxonomicName box="[869,951,733,756]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Frankliniella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varipes">
<emphasis box="[869,951,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">varipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more extensively, or even completely, yellow. 
<taxonomicName box="[240,377,768,792]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Frankliniella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulipes">
<emphasis box="[240,377,768,792]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">F. annulipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[606,675,767,791]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Brazil</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" box="[718,1028,767,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">
Mound and Marullo (
<number box="[962,1020,767,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
from a single female taken from an orchid at Piracicaba (São Paulo).
</paragraph>
